---
title: Creamy Dijon Dill Salmon with Roasted Potatoes & Broccoli
description: This dish features the key to a crowd-pleasing dinner: sauce! Who could turn down a drizzly herb and Dijon concoction—especially one that’s spooned across pan-seared chicken, roasted potatoes, and broccoli? No one, we say! At least not anyone we’ve met. So get ready for the creamiest, most show-stopping sauce celebration you have experienced yet.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/creamy-dijon-dill-chicken-6915220e.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/65ba9d3ef6debb5c45b6ba21.pdf
time required: 30 minutes
author: HelloFresh
cuisine: Mediterranean
nutrition:
  calories: 670 kcal
  fat: 40 g
  saturated fat: 11 g
  carbohydrates: 42 g
  sugar: 6 g
  protein: 36 g
  fiber: 5 g
  sodium: 480 mg
servings: 2
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/creamy-dijon-dill-salmon-65ba9d3ef6debb5c45b6ba21
course: main course
---

Adjust racks to top and middle positions and preheat #oven{} to 450 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Dice @potatoes{12%ounce} into ½-inch pieces. Cut @broccoli{8%ounce} into bite-size pieces if necessary. Pick and finely chop fronds from @dill{¼%ounce}.

Toss potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @cooking oil{} and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Roast on top rack until lightly browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pat @skin-on salmon{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{} and season all over with salt and pepper.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tablespoon} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add salmon and cook until skin is crisp, ~{5-7%minutes}. Flip and cook until cooked through, ~{1-2%minutes} more. Transfer to a #plate{} to rest.

> Salmon is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.

While salmon cooks, toss broccoli on a second baking sheet with a drizzle of oil and a pinch of salt and pepper.

Roast on middle rack until tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Heat pan used for salmon over medium heat. Stir in @chicken stock concentrate{1}, @water{}, and as much chopped dill and @Dijon mustard{2%teaspoon} as you like.

Remove pan from heat; stir in @sour cream{1.5%tablespoon} and @butter{1%tablespoon}, scraping up any browned bits from bottom of pan. Season with salt and pepper.

> TIP: If sauce seems too thick, add more water 1 tsp at a time until it reaches a drizzling consistency.

Divide salmon, potatoes, and broccoli between plates and drizzle with sauce. Garnish with any remaining chopped dill if desired and serve.